1. Motivation:¶

The standard setup of a linear layer in neural network: $ y_{j} = \mathbf{w}_{j}^{T}\mathbf{x}+w_{0j}, \mathbf{w}_{j}\in R^{n},j = 1,2,..,m .$ The reparametrization in weight normaliztion as follows: $$ y_{j} = \frac{g\mathbf{v}_{j}^{T}}{\|\mathbf{v}_{j}\|}\mathbf{x}+w_{0j} $$ The update of $g_{j}$ and $v_{j}$ are respectivaly $$ \delta g_{j} = \frac{\mathbf{w}_{j}^{T}}{\|\mathbf{w}_{j}\|} \big<\frac{\partial E}{\partial \mathbf{w}_{j}}\big>, $$ $$ \delta \mathbf{v}_{j} = \frac{g_{j}}{\|\mathbf{v}_{j}\|} \bigg( \mathbf{I}-\frac{\mathbf{w}_{j}\mathbf{w}_{j}^{T}}{\|\mathbf{w}_{j}\|^{2}} \bigg)\big<\frac{\partial E}{\partial \mathbf{w}_{j}}\big> $$

The relationship of reparametrized model and original model:¶

$$ \begin{bmatrix} \delta w_{0j}\\ \delta \mathbf{w}_{j} \end{bmatrix} =\begin{bmatrix} 1 & \mathbf{0} \\ \mathbf{0}^{T} & \bigg[\frac{\mathbf{w}_{j}\mathbf{w}_{j}^{T}}{\|\mathbf{w}_{j}\|^{2}}+\frac{g^{2}}{\|\mathbf{v}_{j}\|^{2}}\bigg(\mathbf{I}-\frac{\mathbf{w}_{j}\mathbf{w}_{j}^{T}}{\|\mathbf{w}_{j}\|^{2}}\bigg)\bigg] \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} \textstyle \big<\frac{\partial E}{\partial w_{0j}}\big>\\ \textstyle \big<\frac{\partial E}{\partial \mathbf{w}_{j}}\big> \end{bmatrix} $$

We want to understand how the coefficient $\rho_{j}^{2} = \frac{g_{j}^2}{\|v_{j}\|^2} = \frac{\|w_{j}\|^{2}}{\|v_{j}\|^{2}}$ in weight normalization change in each layer as training progresses. We look into how $g_{j}^2$,$ \|v_{j}\|^2$, and $\rho_{j}$ change along the way.¶

2. Experiment details:¶

We did experiment on dataset CIFAR-10 (50,000 training set, 10,000 test) and used the standard setup in LeNet (shown as below), i.e.,

  • SGD with momentum =0.0 and batch-size = 128 images for training (batch-size = 100 images for testing).

  • Learning rate lr = 0.1 at the first 99 epochs, lr = 0.01 at epochs 100 - 199, lr = 0.001 at epochs 200 - 299.

  • No Weight decay: $\hat{J}(w)=J(w)+w_2.$ where $\lambda =0$

LeNet (no dropout):¶

  • #### The weight normalization is applied to the 1st convolution layer.
  • #### No dropout
  • #### Overparametrized model (total parameters 290,486 > image data 50,000)

2. 1 The loss and accuracy in training and testing set.¶

Understand the curve¶

  • There are 2 plots (1st plot is about training loss, and 2nd plot testing accuracy)
  • X-axis is Epoch
  • Curves with different colors means different setup. The legend on the right or left means the following:
    • LeNet: standard setup as a baseline
    • LeNetBN: use batch normalization in all layers
    • LeNetWN1stConvLayer: use weight normalization only in the first layers.
    • LeNetWN: use weight normalization only in all layers.

3. Overviews¶

We look into the dynamics of weight norm that only applied to the first convolution layer instead of all!¶

In the follwing first three cells (each cell has 3 plots), we give you the overviews on the dynamics of $\rho_{j}$, $g_{j}^2$, and $\|v_{j}\|^2$. The following three cells tells about the dynamics of $\rho_{j}$, $g_{j}^2$, and $\|v_{j}\|^2$ for three learning rates:

  • lr = 0.1 for first cell
  • lr = 0.01 for second cell
  • lr = 0.001 for third cell
#¶

Understand the three plots in each cell. Note first that ALL 3 plots share the same X-axis and Y-axis:¶

  • Y-axis is Epoch.
  • X-axis is Neuron. There are 6 neurons of the first convolution net. For each neuron, 3 filters respectively for RGB channels, so the norm $\|\mathbf{v}_{j}\| = \sum_{i=1}^{3}\|\mathbf{v}_{ij}\|, \mathbf{v}_{ij}\in R^{5\times5}, j = 1,2,...,6 $
  • Z-axis is the value in $\rho_{j}$ (Left), $g_{j}$ (Middle), and $\|v_{j}\|$ (Right) respectively.

3.1 Observation:¶

  • #### At learning rate 0.1, $\|v_{j}\|$ (Right) increases monotonically. $g_{j}$ varies (some increase, some decrease and the rest fluctuate). Their ratio $\rho_{j} = \frac{g_{j}} {\|v_{j}\|} $ decreases monotonically due to the fact that $\|v_{j}\|$ is 10 times larger than $g_{j}$. This phenomenon is significant during the first 20 epochs.
  • #### At learning rates 0.01 and 0.001, in most of the cases, the dynamics of $\|v_{j}\|$ and $\rho_{j}$ similar to learning rate 0.1, while $g_{j}$ are all moving downward.
